  Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2tXtQ 'High' avalanche risk The region has been blanketed in heavy snowfall brought by the so-called "Beast from the East" — a blast of Siberian icy weather moving across Europe. According to Jean-Gabriel Delacroy of the Alpes-Maritimes prefecture, warmer temperatures since Thursday have destabilized the fresh buildup of snow. Read more: Deadly 'Beast from the East' winter blizzard batters Europe The Meteo France weather agency had warned there was high chance of avalanches in the area, putting the risk at level four on a scale of one to five. Deputy prefect Gwenaelle Chapuis told local broadcaster BFM that a police inquiry would determine if going off-trail in such conditions "was recklessness or not." A total of 20 people have died on mountain slopes since France's ski season began in November. Last month, an avalanche swept away a man and his 11-year-old daughter in the alpine resort of Val d'Isere. A number of other skiers were also killed in separate incidents in the Pyrenees. Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
